        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <title>GENERAL</title>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The major components of the clutch are the cover assembly and two driven discs separated by an
                        intermediate plate. These clutches are two-plate, pull-type, dry disc design, adjustable and
                        have centrally located springs isolated from the heat of the pressure plate. Dampened driven
                        discs (with springs) and ceramic facings (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100101">Figure 1</hotlnk>) are considered standard and are recommended for
                        most applications. Clutches illustrated have cast iron covers.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <figure id="f1100101" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100101" filename="../figg11/G1100101.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 1. Spicer Clutch</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>In the 14-inch (356 mm) model, the intermediate plate, separating the driven discs, is mounted
                        inside a "pot type" fly- wheel and carried on six drive pins mounted in the flywheel itself.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>In all models, the pressure plate is driven by four drive lugs which mate with four drive
                        slots in the cover. The pressure plate also carries four return springs to retract the pressure
                        plate when the clutch is disengaged.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Maintenance is readily accomplished without special tools other than a hand arbor press, which
                        should be available for easier clutch disassembly and assembly.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>DRIVEN DISC OPTIONS</title>
                    <para>The recommended design discs are the dampened design as shown in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100102">Figure 2</hotlnk>
                        ,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100103">Figure 3</hotlnk>,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100104">Figure 4</hotlnk>and
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100105">Figure 5</hotlnk>. Note the springs around the center hub.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1100102" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100102" filename="../figg11/G1100102.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 2. Recommended Design Discs</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1100103" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100103" filename="../figg11/G1100103.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3. Recommended Design Discs</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1100104" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100104" filename="../figg11/G1100104.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4. Recommended Design Discs</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1100105" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100105" filename="../figg11/G1100105.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 5. Recommended Design Discs</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <para>Clutch disc design applications are dependent on the vehicle engine requirements and operating
                        conditions.
                    </para>
                    <para>The 10-spring disc (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100105">Figure 5</hotlnk>) has four ceramic buttons and ten coaxial springs (a
                        spring within a spring). It has built-in free travel to reduce gear rattle at idle.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>The hub on the 7-spring, 10-spring and 8-spring free travel damper can be turned by
                                hand, depending on the amount of friction lag. This is normal.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>TORQUE LIMITING CLUTCH BRAKE</title>
                    <para>Vehicles with non-synchromesh transmissions use a torque limiting clutch brake (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100106">Figure 6</hotlnk>) that will slip when loads of 20 to 25 ft-lbs. (27
                        to 33 N&#8226;m) are reached. This prevents damaging overloads to the clutch brake. The brake is
                        not designed for upshifting.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1100106" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100106" filename="../figg11/G1100106.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6. Torque Limiting Clutch Brake</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>ANTI-RATTLE SPRINGS</title>
                    <para>The 14-inch (356 mm) Super Duty clutches with their thicker intermediate plate require
                        anti-rattle springs (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100107">Figure 7</hotlnk>). These reduce wear between the intermediate plate
                        and the drive pin, and improve clutch release. If not installed, there is excessive wear to the
                        intermediate plate drive slot which will cause poor clutch release. Anti-rattle springs are
                        positioned as indicated in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100108">Figure 8</hotlnk>with the curved side of the hole facing the flywheel
                        face.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1100107" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100107" filename="../figg11/G1100107.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7. Anti-Rattle Springs</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1100108" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100108" filename="../figg11/G1100108.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 8. Anti-Rattle Spring Positioning</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>SELF-ADJUSTING MECHANISM</title>
                    <para>Some vehicles are equipped with self-adjusting clutches. The self-adjuster mechanism (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100109">Figure 9</hotlnk>) is built into the clutch cover. As facing wear
                        occurs, the normal operating settings for the adjuster mechanism and clutch free pedal are
                        automatically maintained. Refer to
                        <hotlnk document="s11001s_HL1100101.xml" xrefid="hl1100101">ADJUSTMENT</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1100109" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100109" filename="../figg11/G1100109.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 9. Self-Adjuster Mechanism</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <para>Clutches should be replaced when adjustment cannot correct for loss of free pedal or clutch
                        slippage.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>POSITIVE ROLL PIN SEPARATORS</title>
                    <para>The intermediate plate on some 15 1/2" clutches have four roll pins located in the drive lugs
                        to assure equal intermediate plate separation when the clutch is released (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100110">Figure 10</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1100110" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100110" filename="../figg11/G1100110.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 10. Positive Roll Pin Separators</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <specpara>
                        <important>
                            <para>Roll pins must be re-set toward the flywheel whenever new clutch discs or a complete
                                clutch assembly is installed.
                            </para>
                        </important>
                    </specpara>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>ADJUSTING RING</title>
                    <para>Clutch cover assemblies manufactured June 1993 and later have an O-ring seal on the adjusting
                        ring (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100111">Figure 11</hotlnk>). This feature prevents contaminants from entering
                        the threads of the adjusting ring and cover assembly.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1100111" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100111" filename="../figg11/G1100111.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 11. Adjusting Ring O-Ring Seal</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>RELEASE BEARING AND SLEEVE ASSEMBLY</title>
                    <para>Clutch cover assemblies manufactured after November 1993 have a new style release bearing
                        sleeve (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1100112">Figure 12</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1100112" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1100112" filename="../figg11/G1100112.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 12. Release Bearing Sleeve</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
            </geninfo>
